  <h1 style="text-align: center; color: #1976d2; border-bottom: 3px solid #1976d2; padding-bottom: 15px;">
    Model Clauses for Occupation Contracts (Wales)
  </h1>

  <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 10pt; color: #666; margin: 20px 0;">
    Wales | Standard Occupation Contract | Renting Homes (Wales) Act 2016
  </p>

  <div style="background-color: #fff3cd; border-left: 4px solid #ffc107; padding: 15px; margin: 30px 0;">
    <p style="margin: 0; font-weight: bold;">Important Notice</p>
    <p style="margin: 10px 0 0 0;">
      These are the Welsh Government model clauses for Standard Occupation Contracts under the Renting Homes
      (Wales) Act 2016. Your occupation contract incorporates these clauses as required by Welsh law.
      This appendix provides the full text for reference.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>1. Rent</h2>
  <p>
    The Contract-Holder agrees to pay the Rent on the days and in the manner specified in this Contract.
  </p>
  <p>
    Rent is payable in advance. The Landlord may only increase the rent in accordance with the procedure
    set out in the Renting Homes (Wales) Act 2016.
  </p>

  <h2>2. Prohibited Payments</h2>
  <p>
    In accordance with the Renting Homes (Fees etc.) (Wales) Act 2019, the Landlord may not require the
    Contract-Holder to make any prohibited payments. Permitted payments are:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Rent</li>
    <li>A refundable security deposit (maximum 5 weeks' rent if annual rent is less than £50,000, or 6 weeks' rent if £50,000 or more)</li>
    <li>A refundable holding deposit (maximum 1 week's rent)</li>
    <li>Payments to change the contract when requested by the Contract-Holder (capped at £50 or reasonable costs)</li>
    <li>Payments for utilities, communication services, council tax</li>
    <li>Default fees for late payment of rent or lost keys/security devices</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>3. Deposit Protection</h2>
  <p>
    If the Landlord takes a deposit, they must protect it in a government-approved tenancy deposit scheme within
    30 days of receipt. The Landlord must provide prescribed information about the deposit protection to the Contract-Holder.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Deposit Protected With:</strong> {{deposit_scheme}}<br/>
    <strong>Amount:</strong> £{{deposit_amount}}
  </p>

  <h2>4. Written Statement</h2>
  <p>
    The Landlord must provide the Contract-Holder with a written statement of the occupation contract within
    14 days of the occupation date. This statement must contain:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Names of the parties</li>
    <li>The address of the dwelling</li>
    <li>The occupation date</li>
    <li>The amount of rent and when it is payable</li>
    <li>All fundamental, supplementary, and additional terms</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>5. Condition of Property</h2>
  <p>
    The Contract-Holder agrees to:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Keep the dwelling clean and in good condition</li>
    <li>Promptly report any defects or disrepair to the Landlord</li>
    <li>Not damage or alter the dwelling without written consent</li>
    <li>Return the dwelling in the same condition at the end of the contract (fair wear and tear excepted)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>6. Landlord's Obligations</h2>
  <p>
    The Landlord must ensure the dwelling is fit for human habitation and must:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Keep in repair the structure and exterior (including drains, gutters, external pipes)</li>
    <li>Keep in repair and working order the installations for water, gas, electricity, heating, and hot water</li>
    <li>Keep in repair and working order sanitary installations (baths, sinks, toilets)</li>
    <li>Ensure gas and electrical safety certificates are obtained and provided</li>
    <li>Fit smoke alarms on every storey and carbon monoxide alarms where required</li>
    <li>Be registered with Rent Smart Wales</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>7. Access for Repairs</h2>
  <p>
    The Contract-Holder must allow the Landlord reasonable access to inspect the dwelling and carry out repairs,
    subject to giving at least 24 hours' written notice (except in emergencies).
  </p>

  <h2>8. Subletting and Assignment</h2>
  <p>
    The Contract-Holder must not:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Sublet the whole or part of the dwelling</li>
    <li>Assign or transfer the contract</li>
    <li>Take in lodgers</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Without the Landlord's prior written consent.</p>

  <h2>9. Ending the Occupation Contract</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Section 173 Notice (No-fault):</strong> If the Landlord wishes to end a periodic contract without
    giving a reason, they must serve a Section 173 notice giving at least 6 months' notice. A Section 173
    notice cannot be served within the first 6 months of the contract.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Breach Notices:</strong> If the Landlord has grounds for possession (such as rent arrears or breach
    of contract), shorter notice periods may apply under Section 173 or Section 186.
  </p>

  <h2>10. Contract-Holder's Right to Quiet Enjoyment</h2>
  <p>
    The Contract-Holder has the right to "quiet enjoyment" of the dwelling. The Landlord must not interfere with
    the Contract-Holder's use and enjoyment of the dwelling without lawful excuse.
  </p>

  <h2>11. Rent Smart Wales</h2>
  <p>
    All private landlords in Wales must be registered with Rent Smart Wales, and any person carrying out
    letting or management activities must be licensed. It is a criminal offence to let property in Wales
    without registration.
  </p>

